,"1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"About 1070–About 1122":"circa 1070–circa 1122","1110–1141":"1110–1141","1070–1122":"1070–1122","1106":"1106","About 1070":"circa 1070","1122":"1122","1110":"1110","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","About 1122":"circa 1122","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"About 1070–About 1122":"about 1070–about 1122","1110–1141":"1110–1141","1070–1122":"1070–1122","1106":"1106","About 1070":"about 1070","1122":"1122","1110":"1110","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","About 1122":"about 1122","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":16,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":26,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":36,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Bailleul was born about 1070, in Cheshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter. She died about 1122, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"About 1070–About 1122":"umbes 1070–umbes 1122","1110–1141":"1110–1141","1070–1122":"1070–1122","1106":"1106","About 1070":"umbes 1070","1122":"1122","1110":"1110","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","About 1122":"umbes 1122","1070":"1070","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"About 1070–About 1122":"noin 1070–noin 1122","1110–1141":"1110–1141","1070–1122":"1070–1122","1106":"1106","About 1070":"noin 1070","1122":"1122","1110":"1110","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","About 1122":"noin 1122","1070":"1070","Che